fileDesc.title: Serb power plant TENT to see 30% decline in winter output as floods hit coal supply

NAF.raw:
Serb power plant TENT to see 30% decline in winter output as floods hit coal supply
Serbia's largest thermal power plant Termoelektrane Nikola Tesla (TENT) will see production in the winter drop by 30% as its main coal supplier - mining complex Kolubara - was badly hit by the recent floods, news agency Tanjug reported citing TENT's head Cedomir Ponocko.
Now Kolubara delivers 40,000-45,000 tonnes per day and the expected quantity for the next month is to reach 65,000 tonnes per day. Yet, the increase will not be sufficient to reach the level of 90,000 tonnes that is usually supplied in the winter period, Cedomir Ponocko said. Kolubara has four mines and all have been flooded. The complex is crucial for the country's energy system as it provides coal to fuel the Kolubara, Nikola Tesla and Morava thermal power plants, which produce 52% of the total energy. TENT, which is part of state-controlled EPS, remained completely disconnected for nearly ten days in mid-May after suffering enormous damages from the historic rainfalls that poured in the region. The deputy general manager of the state-owned power producer EPS, Zivotije Jovanovic, said that if it's needed, they will import electricity to ensure the winter supply. EPS has imported 161 GWh of electricity for EUR 6.5mn since May 15.
